metadata.name: Boom_fx #19
metadata.description:
Boom_fx, by Stephen Boyd  
July, 2022  
Little India, Toronto, Canada.

Project Description
---
During the short history of fxhash, there have been several important dates marking the growth and evolution of the platform. Boom_fx is a visual interpretation of ten of these days through the lens of real world earthquake data and the colour palettes of Mark Rothko.

Each iteration of Boom_fx represents a window of time on one of these days and expresses the seismic activity that occurred.

These are creative interpretations and while the visual elements and relationships between objects are all based on detailed seismic data from the United States Geological Survey (USGS), they are not meant to be understood as maps.

The ten days were selected for having some significance to the growth and evolution of the fxhash platform and Tezos more broadly.

In chronological order:

1. September 2, 2014 - Tezos White paper released
2. June 30, 2018 - Tezos Initial Release
3. November 6, 2021- Genesis drop on fxhash
4. November 7, 2021 - ciphrd's and punevyr's first drops
5. November 11, 2021 - markknol drops 'SMOLSKULL'
6. December 9, 2021 - zancan drops 'Garden, Monoliths'
7. January 2, 2022 - E0 "The Genesis Drop" of Waiting to be Signed podcast'
8. March 31, 2022 - The Big Burn
9. April 16, 2022 - fxhash 1.0 release
10. March 27, 2022 - Opening day of Art Basel Hong Kong, 2022

There is an eleventh day included: July 18, 2022. This is the last full day of USGS Earthquake data before Boom_fx is published to fxhash.xyz. This date doesn't represent a milestone for the platform, it simply conveys a milestone for the work itself.

The earthquake data comes from the USGS API which very handily provides GeoJSON files. There is further documentation (./documentation/Information_about_boom_fx.md) included with this project that outlines how this data was collected and the information included in these feeds.

Features
--- 
1. Aspect ratios:
- Landscape 62% probability
- Portrait 24% probability
- Square 14% probability

2. Colour Palettes
Eleven Mark Rothko palettes. All equally probable.

3. Date
Each of the eleven days included in this project have an equal probability of being selected.

4. Concurrent minutes sampled during this day
There are six different durations used in this project and they all have an equal probability of being selected.

Interaction
---
Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press t: thumbnail @ a maximum pixel width or height of 200px
- Press s: your current screen size
- Press p: print size @ a maximum pixel width or height of 4800px which is 16"@300dpi
- Press h: HD4K on the vertical @ a maximum pixel width or height of 2160px
- Press m: Max size @ a maximum pixel width or height of 10800px. This is a biiiig size

The filename will include some metadata such as the unique hash, date and time at time of capture.

Data Sources, Software Libraries and VCS / Source Code
--- 

Data Sources
All earthquake data is sourced from the USGS Earthquake API for the International Federation of Digital Seismograph Networks (FDSN). Data was collected in GeoJSON format from the following endpoint: https://earthquake.usgs.gov/fdsnws/event/1/

Software Libraries Used
Made with Processing / P5.js  
p5.js v1.4.1 February 02, 2022

Version Control
https://github.com/sspboyd/boom
This repo is private as of July 2022. However, I have provided a source map with this project so please feel free to browse the code and see how it all works. There are a number of comments in the code explaining what is happening at different points.

metadata.name: Reveries Automata #12
metadata.description:
"The lifetime of a being translated into dualistic combinations. Each individual maintains their perspective of things. Each individual has its pillars and its interferences. A life without concerns can be cleaner and quieter, but undeniably a little chaos can add to the beauty of a whole. It's all about it. Order. Chaos. Singularity is precious. Differences are our riches. Royal beings."

"Reveries Automata" is a generative project that combines AI Art with creative coding. This project was made to be minted on Fxhash and it's inspired on my previous collection "Reveries" where I explore the abstract nuances of art using diffusion models.

I wanted to explore this field of image composition inside creative coding. The solution I came up with was to reveal the images using coded masks.
There are 3 main functions for that:

The Pillars - made basically tiling a separate layer proportionally in the canvas with random sizes, position and rotation (just 2 options for this one, 0 or 90 degrees). Then using this layer as a mask to my base image. Tinted in the colors white, black, blue, red, gold or green.

The Splashes -  A function that makes random ellipses around the canvas in a separate layer, attached in the back and front pillar. And, again, using this layer as a mask to my base image. Tinted in the same color the pillar received.

The Interferences - Probably the one that gave me more trouble to adapt. This funcion is a flow field that uses the color and brightness of my base image to draw and color itself. First I plot particles to use as initial position of the flow and make them draw based on the difference in brightness of my base image. The flow is coloured getting the pixel position of that base image. Tinted in the colors white, gold or black.

To support those code functions and to make sure that the outputs will have many variations, I've prompted and composited 40 base images that are used as background, patterns, textures, flow drawing/colouring and frames.

There are concrete textures, painting flow textures and golden foil textures for background and pillars; Rough contrasted painting flows (white and gold) for the interferences; Labyrinth, Rectangular and Copacabana patterns; 6 paper frames variations to finalize the composition.

Press "G" to save currebt .png canvas.

Read more about: https://brunomerli.com/reveries-automata

metadata.name: La Pedrera Serie 1 #103
metadata.description:
This project is inspired from Gaud√≠'s Casa Mil√† in Barcelona, also known as La Pedrera. 

This is the first part of a 2-part-serie based on La Pedrera.

In this project, which is intentionaly saturated in color, you will recognize an abstract reproduction of the curved floors and windows of La Casa Mil√†.

The colors are accentued by the flowers disseminated on each floor. 

Main features of this project include:
- Palette: 10 colors,
- Texture: Strong or Soft,
- Noise: True or False,
- Strong Lines: True or False,
- Flower Packing: Mini or Maxi.

In live mode, press [s] to save a 1200 x 1500 (4 DPI) version of the mint.

Thanks a lot to everyone who will mint a token! :)

metadata.name: Origin Undecided #16
metadata.description:
These feel like communications from an unknown place.

Ultimately, this is a deeper exploration of familiar concepts. The code generates patterns for a couple million lines, each with extremely low opacity. As they're drawn and overlap, the color accumulates and shapes begin to form.

Created by Eric Davidson. 2022.

metadata.name: alchemy(maxima) #66
metadata.description:
This collection takes its main inspiration from the Turkish marbling art ‚ÄúEbru‚Äù and tries to spin it with a golden twist, hence alchemy :) 

alchemy(maxima) tries to create a composition either using one of the two grid types, and sometimes breaking them or in a totally chaotic way, but uses color harmony and rhythm to keep the chaos in check and the resulting image still somewhat interesting and sometimes golden-ish‚Ä¶

The name includes ‚Äúmaxima‚Äù because this is the first part of a 2-part series; its companion collection ‚Äúalchemy(minima)‚Äù will be released soon and as per my tradition will be freely available to maxima holders.

From the proceeds of the primary sales of alchemy(maxima),

- 33% will directly go to The Processing Foundation,
- 33% will fund the greater evil,
- 34% will be used to grow my collection.

So in a way, all the proceeds will go back into the ecosystem. This is my way of making up for taking tez out with my donations earlier.

If you are wondering what the hell ‚Äúthe greater evil‚Äù is, read about it here : 

https://twitter.com/evilnft/status/1544320804304961536?s=20&t=AoEfLfn32tGNR8JTi5Jjng

And find it here:

https://www.fxhash.xyz/u/the%20greater%20evil/collection

‚Äî

About the work: 

- 22 palettes - 7 new, 15 recycled,
- 3 main variants,
- 4 sub-variants each,
- 9 visible and some hidden features :)
- After going live, press ‚Äús‚Äù to save a png (at your screen resolution)
- No hi-res output due to the warp manipulating the pixel array directly, which means higher res equals to much higher computation time.

Thank you all in advance and have a good day!

Warp functions are based on this article by Inigo Quilez : https://iquilezles.org/articles/warp/

DISCLAIMER : I am not a good coder, I have tried to fix my past mistakes from my earlier projects to make some room for new mistakes :) I am learning on the way and certainly hoping that there aren't any huge bugs or anything, so you can enjoy your mint! Please hit me up if you have any concerns after minting and we can discuss a solution.

metadata.name: Ethereal Microcosm #227
metadata.description:
An exploration of algorithmic organisms in a contained environment.

This piece is about the simulation of microscopic patterns using a high number of even tinier agents all following the same rules. Different species evolve and interact together, resulting in stabilizing patterns out of their parametric configurations. A form of artificial life.

This work is based on the paper "Characteristics of pattern formation and evolution in approximations of physarum transport networks", written by Jeff Jones and popularized in the artistic field by Sage Jenson. Some features were added to increase the visual and behavioral complexity of the system. Agents are divided into different species, with their own set of rules and interacting with their own substrate. Substrates also interact with each other and agents will mutate in contact of some of them.

NFT License
Runs properly on Chrome 97.0.4692.99
GPU intensive
